04736nam a22005895i 9780226108520DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802261085207 a10.7208/97802261085202doi  a(DE-B1597)523160  a(OCoLC)884016212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJC336b.H254 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a320.012231 aHale, Piers J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitical Descent :bMalthus, Mutualism, and the Politics of Evolution in Victorian England /cPiers J. Hale. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b17 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Politics of Evolution -- t1. Every Cheating Tradesman: The Political Economy of Natural Selection -- t2. A Very Social Darwinist: Herbert Spencer's Lamarckian Radicalism -- t3. A Liberal Descent: Charles Darwin and the Evolution of Ethics -- t4. Liberals and Socialists: The Politics of Evolution in Victorian England -- t5. Malthus or Mutualism? Huxley, Kropotkin, and the Moral Meaning of Darwinism -- t6. Of Mice and Men: Malthus, Weismann, and the Future of Socialism -- t7. Fear of Falling: Evolutionary Degeneration and the Politics of Panmixia -- tConclusion: Political Descent: Anticipations of the Twentieth Century and Beyond -- tAfterword: Engaging the Present -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHistorians of science have long noted the influence of the nineteenth-century political economist Thomas Robert Malthus on Charles Darwin. In a bold move, Piers J. Hale contends that this focus on Malthus and his effect on Darwin's evolutionary thought neglects a strong anti-Malthusian tradition in English intellectual life, one that not only predated the 1859 publication of the Origin of Species but also persisted throughout the Victorian period until World War I. Political Descent reveals that two evolutionary and political traditions developed in England in the wake of the 1832 Reform Act: one Malthusian, the other decidedly anti-Malthusian and owing much to the ideas of the French naturalist Jean Baptiste Lamarck. These two traditions, Hale shows, developed in a context of mutual hostility, debate, and refutation. Participants disagreed not only about evolutionary processes but also on broader questions regarding the kind of creature our evolution had made us and in what kind of society we ought therefore to live. Significantly, and in spite of Darwin's acknowledgement that natural selection was "the doctrine of Malthus, applied to the whole animal and vegetable kingdoms," both sides of the debate claimed to be the more correctly "Darwinian." By exploring the full spectrum of scientific and political issues at stake, Political Descent offers a novel approach to the relationship between evolution and political thought in the Victorian and Edwardian eras.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEvolution (Biology) and the social scienceszEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aEvolution (Biology)xPolitical aspects. 0aMalthusianismxPolitical aspects. 0aMutualismzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitical sciencezEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial DarwinismxPolitical aspects. 0aSocial evolutionxPolitical aspects. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226108520423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226108520.j